      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "c76786fa6963ed83",
        "text": "Thus, the computer acquires a communicative meaning comparable to the communicative function of persons. Computers, as Fuchs (1991: 3) provocatively remarks, \"are finally information transmitters, information receivers, and information processors par excellence. Taking this into account, their communication behavior differs from human communication behavior at most by precision and speed, when it comes to the access time for the processing and output of information (...)\". The computer is a (machine-)technology, which -just like persons of ongoing communication- \"(...) conveys to a sufficient extent both normal conformity and ongoing irritation (...)\" (Luhmann, 1992: 2). (Luhmann, 1992: 2). Like persons, the computer provides signals that can be 'read' as information and messages in the communication process. This peculiar coupling of the computer to communication processes may be the reason why it is often formulated in everyday life as well as in social science communication contexts as a 'communication partner' that can be and is used to build up socio-technical interaction processes (cf. also Geser, 1989)."
